<b><p class = "edu">As a teacher, how do you feel when students start laughing in a classroom?</b></p>
<p>During a sex-ed session I once asked students to comment on the risk of condoms splitting. “It depends,” one student shouted out. It was uncharacteristically thoughtful sounding for this student, so I was keen to follow it up. “On what?” I asked.

“Whether you’ve got a big jumbo,” he said. Everyone laughed except me. I was annoyed, because he’d set me up, but as a teacher there was a case that I should challenge him for trivialising an important issue.

It’s easy to feel like a chump when students laugh, which I guess is how I felt that time. Other times, like when I accidentally walk backwards into a trolley while explaining something, it’s easier to laugh at yourself. And obviously if you’ve cracked a joke, it’s a wonderful feeling when the students laugh.

Basically it depends on your relationship with the students and the class as a whole. Some students will enjoy a bad natured laugh at the teacher’s expense and that doesn’t feel great. It especially makes you question whether you the teacher are guilty of teaching the class in an alienating way, which can be difficult to avoid when you have to force students to learn difficult things they’re not naturally interested in.

What’s really nice is when everyone can enjoy a genuine laugh together. I had a student who liked to crack a lot of jokes. “Do you like chimney jokes, Sir? I’ve got stacks of them. Next one’s on the house,” he’d say. One time he asked my permission to tell a joke, which concerned me. “As long as it’s clean,” I said. “Only tell a joke you’d be happy to tell your granny.”

“My granny’s worse than me,” he replied. All of us laughed.</p>
